features.optionalDescription: An order of tailless amphibians which is comprised of frogs and toads.
Any activity or feature of the landscape that causes an increase in risk of wildfire, either in the immediate sense (risk of fire escaping a project area), or in the longer term.

The overland water flow that occurs when precipitation from rain or meltwater hits impermeable ground or soil that is infiltrated to full capacity, and the excess water flows over the land. Surface runoff can occur in natural habitats or in areas with high cover of concrete or roads. This is a more localized process than Surface Flow Pattern, which refers to overall flow across a landscape.
The sprouting of seeds into plants, or spores into sporelings. Germination rates or success can be impacted by changes in water, oxygen, temperature, or nutrients.
Turbidity is the cloudiness or haziness of a fluid caused by large numbers of individual particles that are generally invisible to the naked eye.
Something that lies on, over, or around something in order to protect or conceal it.
Vegetation found in association with wetland habitats.
Horseshoe crabs are marine arthropods of the family Limulidae and order Xiphosura or Xiphosurida, that live primarily in and around shallow ocean waters on soft sandy or muddy bottoms.
Scouring flows are water flows at a velocity high enough to remove significant sediment, soil, vegetation, or other structures.
The number of plants per unit area. Density counts are generally done on individual plant species, and are not equivalent to biomass or cover.

Under-cut banks rise vertically or overhang the stream. They may be naturally occurring, but modifications of channel or streamflow can cause the undercutting to be too severe, causing the bank to collapse. Under-cut banks can provide good habitat for macroinvertebrates or fish species.
A part of a stream or river that is not part of the main channel and is characterized by little or no streamflow.
The cross-sectional width of a stream or river.
A beaten path through non-developed habitat, such as a forest, grassland, or riparian habitat.
A flat expanse of ground covered with salt and other minerals.
Old, aging, or dead plants or plant material.
An aquifer is any geologic formation containing groundwater. Often, it consists of water-saturated permeable rock, gravel, or sand. The upper portion of an aquifer is often known as the water table.
The boundary of forest patches where trees transition to another habitat type (e.g. field, open water) or physical characteristic (e.g. road, building).
The loss of soil that occurs from the banks of streams and rivers due to the flow of water.

Evaporation is the molecular change of a substance from liquid to gas. Evaporation is an important component of the water cycle in which heat from the sun powers the evaporation process. It soaks up moisture from soil, as well as the biggest oceans and lakes.
The lateral confines of a stream, river, or channel. The margins are typically characterized by shallow, warmer waters with less current but can vary significantly.
Airspace above vegetation height free of obstacles to flight
Recreational activities (e.g., fishing, biking, and hiking) that occur off established roads, trails, and paths.
A person traveling by foot,

The water table is the uppermost zone of the saturated portion of the ground or aquifer, or the boundary between the saturated and unsaturated portions of the ground. The depth of the water table can be affected by seasons, precipitation, vegetation, and anthropogenic factors.

Tamarisk refers to a group of large shrubs or small trees within the genus Tamarix. Tamarisk is extremely invasive, competing with native riparian species for water and space. They are more drought tolerant than native species, and their ability to sequester salt in their foliage can lead to saline leaf litter and soil conditions and further exclude native riparian species. However, some native bird species do nest in tamarisk.

Water quality overall refers to the chemical, biological, physical, and radiological qualities of water. The so-called quality of water for any particular purpose is highly variable, but in this context, it is used as a general term for the condition of water needed to maintain species or habitat conditions.

Raptors are birds of prey. In North America, hawks, eagles, harriers, kites, falcons, and osprey are considered to be raptors. Vultures and condors were previously considered raptors, however, DNA evidence has shown that vultures are more closely related to the Ciconiiformes (storks), or that they belong in their own class.
A decrease in the number of nests available to the animal via removal.
Blowouts are depressions, either conical or irregular in nature, in open, bare sand areas that are caused by high winds and sand that has been exposed by high levels of disturbance.

A cactus is a member of the plant family cactaceae within the order Caryophyllales. Cacti are succulent perennials that are native to arid and semi-arid regions. Cacti store water, and are often ribbed or fluted, which allows them to expand and contract easily. Cacti occur in a wide range of shapes and sizes.
The ability of the soil to remain unchanged.
Gathering place for males to engage in competitive displays for the purposes of mating during the breeding season .

Habitat or ecological succession is the gradual process by which habitats develop and change over time. The process of succession can take anywhere from several years to several millenia to complete. The process is often triggered by a disturbance event such as a fire or flood. It is often divided into two categories: primary succession and secondary succession.
The land alongside or sloping down to a river, stream, creek, or lake.

The act in which a organism uses host individuals, either of the same or different species, to raise the young of the brood-parasite. This relieves the parasitic parent from the investment of rearing young or building nests, enabling them to spend more time foraging, producing offspring etc.

Sediment transport is the amount and size of sediment that a river carries. Sediment transport is determined by three main factors: competence (the size of a particle a river can move, based primarily on river speed), capacity (the maximum amount of sediment a stream can carry, based on channel gradient, discharge and the calibre of the sediment load), and sediment supply (the amount and size of sediment available).
Noise related to the movement of foot traffic into and out of an area.
A substance that attracts animals
Sources of freshwater that may be used by both animals and humans. This can include both natural and man-made sources.

Wild Blue Lupine is a perennial plant, found on dry, sandy soils in open- to partially-shaded habitat. It has multiple flowers growing on each stalk, ranging in color from pink to blue. It is the sole food source for Karner Blue Butterfly Larvae.
Groundwater contamination occurs when pollutants of any type seep into the groundwater supply.
A plant cultivated for its grain-like seeds and as a cover crop.
Mollusks are a group of species in the Mollusca phylum.  Mollusks make up a significant part of marine invertebrates that serve as a source of nutrition for many species.
Non-vascular, non-seed producing plants. Mosses, and liverworts are common examples.
The blowout penstemon is a pioneer species so it requires open sand areas to colonize.
Cultivated plants found in croplands and agriculture fields like corn, soybeans, wheat, etc..
The temporary or permanent placement of materials or structures which inhibit movement of animals through their habitat
To bury or trap a species.  For example, a project proponent could cover the entrance of a tortoise burrow while leveling a project area, thus entombing the tortoise.
Moss of the genus Sphagnum, of temperate bogs, having leaves capable of holding much water.  Layers of these mosses decay to form peat.  Also called peat moss or bog moss.

Is a fire in an area of combustible vegetation that occurs in the countryside or rural area. Depending on the type of vegetation where it occurs, a wildfire can also be classified more specifically as a brush fire, forest fire, or grass fire.
Wave scour is the removal by hydrodynamic forces of granular bed material in the vicinity of Coastal Structures.

Snowshoe hare a species of hare that have adapted to living in deep snow conditions by developing physical characteristics of their feet that work to displace weight along the lines of snowshoes.  They are present in the northern United States and most of Canada.
Illuminance is a measure of how much of the incident light illuminates the surface. Illuminance was formerly refereed to as brightness.
Atlantic herring (Clupea harengus) is a herring in the family Clupeidae. It is one of the most abundant fish species in the world.

Pollination is the process by which pollen is transferred from the anther (male part) to the stigma (female part) of the plant, thereby enabling fertilization and reproduction. Biological pollination occurs when a living organisms aids in the transfer of pollen.

Zooplankton are free-living, non-photosynthetic organisms primarily comprised of protists, rotifers, and crustaceans. Most species are microscopic that float, drift, or weakly swim in the water column. Zooplankton makes up an essential part of an ecosystems food web.
Ash is the end product of incomplete combustion will be mostly mineral, but usually still contain an amount of combustible organic or other oxidizable residues.
All of the biological organisms that exist within an area and how they are structured.

An inadvertent return is the unintended transfer of drilling mud to the surface during boring machine operations by way of fractures or fissures that occur naturally, rather than as a result of boring operations.
A transparent and nearly colorless chemical substance that is the main constituent of Earth's streams, lakes, and oceans, and the fluids of most living organisms.

The Emergent Wetland Class is characterized by erect, rooted, herbaceous hydrophytes, excluding mosses and lichens. This vegetation is present for most of the growing season in most years. These wetlands are usually dominated by perennial plants. All water regimes are included except subtidal and irregularly exposed.

A boundary created by the convergence of two different habitats. A host of species exploit the unique conditions of the edge habitat or cross between the two habitats utilizing resources and affecting both ecosystems.

Bryophyte is a traditional name used to refer to all embryophytes (land plants) that do not have true vascular tissue and are therefore called "non-vascular plants". Some bryophytes do have specialized tissues for the transport of water; however, since these do not contain lignin, they are not considered to be true vascular tissue.

Mammals are any members of a clade of endothermic amniotes distinguished from reptiles and birds by the possession of hair, three middle ear bones, mammary glands, and a neocortex. The mammalian brain regulates body temperature and the circulatory system, including the four-chambered heart.
This is in reference to the preferred site for the species.  An example would be a plant that prefers the northern bank of a river.
Low-lying land, typically by a river and subject to overflow during floods.
For species who live underground any change in the surface structure could potentially impact the species habitat structure

For a species living underground any changes to the surface structure could impact the species habitat structure. Being that the species habitat is considered underground we cannot say habitat structure. Therefore we use surface structure.
rusting of metals
Substance that provides nourishment essential for growth and the maintenance of life. This can include nutrients to water and soil.
A dry creek or stream bed with temporary, intermittent, or seasonal flows after a significant rain event. This term often applys to sloped areas or mountainous terrain in desert climates.
Vegetation which is submerged throughout its life cycle. This includes submerged vegetation in freshwater, estuarine, and marine waters.
Plant Species: Lupinus albifrons (silver lupine), L. varicolor (manycolored lupine), and L. formosus (summer lupine). These lupines are shrubs or perennial herbs that are native to California.
Organic matter that has died and is in the process of decay, introducing nutrients into the environment.
Any material used for the primary purposes of changing elevation, filling voids, replacing an aquatic area with dry land, or changing the bottom elevation of a waterbody.

Agave is a genus of monocots. The plants are perennial, but each rosette flowers once and then dies. They are succulents with a large rosette of thick, fleshy leaves, each ending generally in a sharp point and with a spiny margin; the stout stem is usually short, the leaves apparently springing from the root.

A fan or cone-shaped sediment deposit formed by a stream, either where it issues from a narrow mountain valley onto a plain or broad valley, or where a tributary stream joins a main stream. When several neighboring alluvial fans converge into a single fan of deposits against a slope, it is known as a compound alluvial fan, or a bajada.

Geographic aspect refers to the horizontal direction to which a mountain slope faces. For example, a slope on the eastern edge of the Rockies toward the Great Plains is described as having an easterly aspect.
The amount of vegetative cover that is provided on the ground.
The total area of a species' habitat
Any worm that lives in a marine environment is considered a marine worm.  These worms serve as significant members of the marine diet.
The amount of ground covered by water. Inundation is typically associated with increased streamflow or flooding as normally dry soil becomes submerged.

Macroinvertebrates are animals without a backbone that can be seen with the naked eye. These bottom-dwelling animals include crustaceans and worms but most are aquatic insects. Beetles, caddisflies, stoneflies, mayflies, hellgrammites, dragonflies, true flies, and some moths are among the groups of insects represented in streams. Macroinvertebrates are an important link in the food web between the producers (leaves, algae) and higher consumers such as fish.
An invisible gaseous substance surrounding the earth composed of a mixture mainly of oxygen and nitrogen that does not contain substances that have harmful or poisonous effects.
This is a wetland type that may also be referred to a forested swamp or palustrine forested wetland.
A geological process in which erosion deepens the channel of a stream or valley by removing material from the stream's bed or the valley's floor.

Turbidity is a measure of suspended particles within water; specifically, how much the suspended solids decrease the passage of light through the liquid. The suspended solids could include sediment, algae, plankton, or microbes. Turbidity can impact temperature and dissolved oxygen concentration.
Any physical feature that facilitates wildlife movement.

Hummingbirds are birds from the Americas that constitute the family Trochilidae. They are among the smallest of birds, most species measuring 7.513 cm (35 in) in length. Indeed, the smallest extant bird species is a hummingbird, the 5 cm (2.0 in) bee hummingbird weighing less than 2.0 g (0.07 oz).
Comparative darkness and coolness caused by shelter from direct sunlight
a substance that provides nourishment essential for growth and the maintenance of life.
Vegetation along the edge of a forested habitat.
Actions that are done by humans that benefit the species in some way.  An example would be the introduction to prey or the opening of corridors.

The type of wildlife habitat found along the banks of a river, stream, lake or other body of water. Riparian habitats are ecologically diverse and may be home to a wide range of plants, insects and amphibians that make them ideal for different species of birds.

An elevated area rising above the general level of a wetland area. Hummock is a general term that can refer to many different types of similar features found in diverse habitat types and with multiple morphological and geological characteristics.
Paths/trails with trees or other woody plants on either side.
Enlarged portion of plants, either stems or roots, that are generally used for energy storage.
instream flow is seasonal
The occurrence, circulation, distribution, and properties of surface and subsurface water.

A  small or strictly localized flora (as of a microenvironment); 
the community of microorganisms, including algae, fungi, and bacteria that live in or on another living organism or in a particular habitat
Shrimp are crustaceans that have a significant role in the marine environment as a source of food.
The collective route that surface water takes as it flows in a watershed. Surface flow pattern is also strongly affected by the topography of an area.
When an animal feeds on ground vegetation
An upwelling of ground water that creates a spring head.
The ability of prey to recolonize an area after disturbance.
The depth in which sunlight can reach.
Narrow, horizontal surfaces that projects out from a wall, cliff, or other surface

Surface flow is specified as the lateral movement of surface water in a system, such as wetlands, streams, rivers, lakes or surface runoff. Typically surface flow includes the movement of all surface water within a landscape, however, there are more specific features available to designate specific flow types, such as stream flow or surface runoff.
A large grouping of Common Terns (Sterna hirundo).

Any physical structures present on a landscape that are distinct from living vegetation and provide some vertical and horizontal variation. Structures may be inorganic, (i.e. rocks, boulders) or may be organic (i.e. tree stumps, driftwood, boards).

An ecosystem's response to the addition of artificial or natural nutrients, mainly phosphates, through detergents, fertilizers, or sewage, to an aquatic system. One example is the "bloom" or great increase of phytoplankton in a water body as a response to increased levels of nutrients.
For Mexican spotted owl, most nest sites are in natural tree cavities. Most nest sites are used for more than 1 year and are typically 60 - 100 feet high.
house, bat box, bridge
A sandbar is a characteristically linear landform completely within or extending into a body of water. It is typically composed of sand, silt, and/or small pebbles.
open water shading creates predator habitat and is actively avoided by the species.
Water released from the zone of saturation. Releases may be in the form of springs, seeps, etc.
Empty voids between rocks. Often used for cover from predators, foraging habitat for small invertebrates, or conduit passageways toward deeper habitat.
The surface or medium upon which a substance grows, or to which it is attached. Substrates can be biotic or abiotic in nature.
The transportation of nutrients through part or all of an ecosystem

Herbivores, such as deer, rabbits, or voles, selectively browse vegetation (preference for certain species, stage of vegetation development, etc) and not others. This activity is much more selective than grazing.
Water's dissolved mineral content
Stems refer to the thinnest sand smallest extensions of plants.  These can be used as food source or as cover by individuals.
A feature that accumulates on the ground or on plants that is used by species to their advantage by taking advantage of camouflage and physical restrictions.
A rock is a naturally occurring solid aggregate of one or more minerals or mineraloids.

Areas with low current speeds, within an environment with higher velocity water. Usually have high sediment stability, can be characterized by a depositional environment, usually located in shallow areas or behind boulders in streams.
shallow, moving water
Any plant, whether it is native to a habitat or not, that has the ability to thrive and spread aggressively within that habitat.

Ants are eusocial insects of the family Formicidae and, along with the related wasps and bees, belong to the order Hymenoptera. Ants evolved from wasp-like ancestors in the mid-Cretaceous period between 110 and 130 million years ago and diversified after the rise of flowering plants.
a reserve of viable seeds present in the soil and on its surface
Phosphorus is required for plants, however, excess amounts result in leaf chlorosis. By limiting  other vital nutrients such as: iron, manganese, and zinc.

Nitrogen is considered to be an essential element required for successful plant growth. If nitrate is not absorbed by plant roots, it is washed away by runoff. The phytoavailability of nitrogen increases when excess nitrogen is applied, which increases the potential threat to the surrounding environment, such as eutrophication.
Any item that is originally used or created by humans.  This commonly includes tires, boxes, etc.
A bay is a large body of water connected to an ocean or sea formed by an inlet of water due to the surrounding land blocking some waves and often reducing winds.
A very small stream.
trampling of riparian vegetation by humans in riparian environment

Bees are flying insects closely related to wasps and ants, known for their role in pollination and, in the case of the best-known bee species, the European honey bee, for producing honey and beeswax. Bees are a monophyletic lineage within the superfamily Apoidea, presently considered as a clade Anthophila.
The red squirrel is a species of squirrel that is present in North America.  Their diet consists primarily of coniferous seeds.
The amount of area that an individual of a species needs in order to carry out basic life functions.
In vascular plants, the root is the organ of a plant that typically lies below the surface of the soil.

Many species, whether they are native to a location or not, that has the ability to thrive and spread aggressively within that habitat is considered invasive. The invasive species stressor, in this case, includes invertebrates, mammals, etc, but does not include plants.
The ability of vegetative strip or buffer to filter out excess sediment and nutrients. Usually in the riparian zone but may include the surrounding uplands.
The accidental or intentional mating of organisms of different strains or species.
Blowouts are conical or round depressions in the sand caused by wind erosion when the vegetative cover has been disturbed or removed.
This refers to the length of time that a pond or pool can retain water.
Inundation means to be covered with water.
Roosts can include cracks, crevices, cavities, and exfoliating bark on trees.
A naturally occurring storage of seeds that are often dormant.
Species of the genus Sambucus (elderberry). Consists of from one to four species. The taxonomy is currently undergoing revision.
decrease in vegetative cover for feeding and sheltering
Microscopic organisms, which may be single celled or multicellular. The category includes, but is not limited to, algae, zooplankton, phytoplankton, bacteria, diatoms, etc.
overhanging trees, logs, wood debris in a river or stream

A seed is an embryonic plant enclosed in a protective outer covering. The formation of the seed is part of the process of reproduction in seed plants, the spermatophytes, including the gymnosperm and angiosperm plants. Seeds are the product of the ripened ovule, after fertilization by pollen and some growth within the mother plant. The embryo is developed from the zygote and the seed coat from the integuments of the ovule.

A cinega is a wetland system unique to the American Southwest. Cinagas are alkaline, freshwater, spongy, wet meadows with shallow-gradient, permanently saturated soils in arid landscapes that often occupied nearly the entire widths of valley bottoms. That description satisfies historic, pre-damaged cinagas, although few can be described that way now. Incised cinagas are common today and are usually associated with seeps or springs, found in canyon headwaters or along stream margins.
Hole in the air

Microbial mats formed on the water surface or on the surface of rocks. It is made out of blue-green cyanobacteria and sediments. It is formed by having alteration layers between the blue-green bacteria and sediments, creating dark-laminated layers.
Rubble, wreckage, ruins, litter and discarded garbage/refuse/trash, scattered remains of something destroyed, discarded, or as in geology, large rock fragments left by a melting glacier etc.
Aquatic habitat is any inundated area in the landscape
A complex mixture of algae, cyanobacteria, heterotrophic microbes, and detritus that is attached to submerged surfaces in most aquatic ecosystems.
An elevated area that raptors, or other aerial predators, may use to rest or perch on while searching for available prey.
DO NOT USE: WILL BE DELETED
Water beneath the surface of the ground, consisting largely of surface water that has seeped down:  the source of water in springs and wells.

features.displayName: soil composition to test ( NOT SHARED)

features.optionalDescription: a resource for the UAT demo
Streams with surface flow year around.
Alteration of the habitat which reduces the usefulness of the habitat for a species.

lalalalaWhen defining a new feature, you must categorize it as either a resource or non-resource. Both feature types are used when defining effects pathways, but only resource-type features are used when describing a species' resource needs.

Before creating a new feature, try to use an existing one even if the term is slightly different than your desired term. Creating a new feature should be reserved for features that are truly unique and missing from the list.

Note: A new feature is give
This is a measure of the acidity or alkalinity of the water resource.
Pools in streams and rivers
A small sheltered bay in the coastline of a river or lake.
Space between the solid particles that compose substrates and soils.

Invertebrates are animals that lack a backbone and includes groups such as sponges, cnidarians, flatworms, molluscs, arthropods, insects, segmented worms, and echinoderms as well as many other lesser-known groups of animals.
Describe a linear relationship between a resource need and available food resources.
A medium-sized predator.
Areas that are inundated or saturated by surface or groundwater at a frequency and duration sufficient to support, a prevalence of vegetation typically adapted for life in saturated soil conditions.
Use of SCUBA or Snorkel to assess species status in the project area.
Current is the flow of water over a certain point as it moves downstream. Current varies spatially and temporally.
As you develop Effect Pathways involving changes to Hydrologic regime

Biological corridor is the designation for a continuous geographic extent of  habitat linking ecosystems, either spatially or functionally; such a link restores or conserves the connection between habitats that are fragmented by natural causes or human development.

An insect is a class of invertebrate from the phyllum Arthropod. At its most basic, insects have a chitinous exoskeleton, three sets of jointed legs, one set of antennae, and their bodies are divided into three parts (head, thorax, and abdomen).
The acorn, or oak nut, is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera Quercus and Lithocarpus, in the family Fagaceae)

Soil is the mixture of minerals, organic matter, gases, liquids and a myriad of organisms that can support plant life. It is a natural body that exists as part of the pedosphere and it performs four important functions: it is a medium for plant growth; it is a means of water storage, supply and purification; it is a modifier of the atmosphere; and it is a habitat for organisms that take part in decomposition and creation of a habitat for other organisms.

A fish is any member of a paraphyletic group of organisms that consist of all gill-bearing aquatic craniate animals that lack limbs with digits. Included in this definition are the living hagfish, lampreys, and cartilaginous and bony fish.

Compaction is a process in which stress is applied to the soil causing densification as air is displaced from the pores between the soil grains. Normally, compaction is the result of heavy machinery compressing the soil, but it can also occur due to the passage of foot traffic from humans or animals.
Resistance of substrate particle movement in response to different flows.
The amount of oxygen that is dissolved or carried in a given medium (e.g., water).
A measure of how much oxygen is dissolved in the water.  Measured in mg/L.

An arthropod is an invertebrate animal having an exoskeleton (external skeleton), a segmented body, and jointed appendages. Arthropods form the phylum Arthropoda, and include the insects, arachnids, and crustaceans

Crustaceans form a very large group of arthropods which includes crabs, lobsters, crayfish, shrimp, krill and barnacles. The 67,000 described species range in size from 0.1 mm 3.8 m. Like other arthropods, crustaceans have an exoskeleton, which they moult to grow. They are distinguished from other groups of arthropods by the possession of biramous (two-parted) limbs, and by the nauplius form of the larvae.
Reptiles are ectothermic animals in the class Reptilia. Reptiles include turtles, crocodilians, lizards, snakes, and tuatara.
This refers to the distance from other habitats or species.  An example would be that one species needs to be at least 500 yards from man-made structures.
Stream without barriers (e.g., dams, beaverdams) impeding flow.
Many species and pollinators rely on a multitude of native desert species to fulfill their life history needs, as opposed to a specific plant species or a specific set of plant species.
The pH level of the soil.

Any member of more than 65,000 animal species belonging to the class Gastropoda, the largest group in the phylum Mollusca. The class is made up of the snails, which have a shell into which the animal can generally withdraw, and the slugssnails whose shells have been reduced to an internal fragment or completely lost in the course of evolution.

The soil pH is a measure of the acidity or alkalinity in soils. pH is defined as the negative logarithm (base 10) of the activity of hydronium ions (H+) in a solution. In water, it normally ranges from -1 to 14, with 7 being neutral. A pH below 7 is acidic and above 7 is alkaline. Soil pH is considered a master variable in soils as it controls many chemical processes that take place. It specifically affects plant nutrient availability. The optimum pH range for most plants is between 5.5 and 7.0.
Gill-bearing aquatic craniate animals that lack limbs with digits
Subterranean voids are openings below the surface. This can include features such as caves, mines, or burrows.
Streamflow is the flow of water in streams, rivers, and other channels.
To be deleted once system is debugged.

Rodents are mammals of the order Rodentia. Most are small animals with robust bodies and a single pair of incisors in each jaw that grows continuously through the animal's life. Animals classified in Rodentia include rats, mice, beavers, muskrats, porcupines, chipmunks, squirrels, prairie dogs, and voles.
Shoreline is the edge of a body of water where the intersection of water and land occurs.
Human debris is man-made rubble, wreckage, ruins, litter and discarded garbage/refuse/trash, scattered remains of something destroyed and discarded.
A river that runs year round

Insects from the order Hymenoptera, including wasps, bees, sawflies, and ants. They typically have four wings, and the females have an ovipositor that is often modified by stinging. Hymenopterans undergo complete metamorphasis, wtih egg, larva, pupa, and adult stages. Many hymenopterans are well-known as pollinators.

Amphibians are ectothermic, tetrapod vertebrates of the class Amphibia. Amphibians typically begin life in an aquatic larval form but undergo metamorphosis into an adult air-breathing form. Amphibians use their moist skin as either a primary or secondary respiratory surface.
A large phylum of segmented worms that includes earthworms, ragworms, and leeches. Annelids are bilaterally symmetrical, coelomate organisms.

Arachnids are a group of arthropods that include spiders, ticks, mites, scorpions and harvestmen. Arachnids have two main body segments and four pairs of jointed legs. In some groups of arachnids such as mites and hooded tickspiders, the larval stages have only three pairs of legs and fourth leg pair appears after they develop into nymphs. Arachnids have an exoskeleton that must be shed periodically in order for the animal to grow.

A brood-parasite that makes no nest, but instead lays her eggs in the nests of other bird species, who then raise the young cowbirds, usually at the expense at the expense of some of the host's own chicks. Cowbird eggs hatch faster than other species eggs, giving cowbird nestlings a head start in getting food from the parents. Young cowbirds also develop at a faster pace than their nest mates, and they sometimes toss out eggs and young nestling or smother them in the bottom of the nest.

Creosote bush is a dominant shrub of arid habitats in the southwestern U.S. This species has a root system that is extremely efficient at absorbing water, to the extent that it excludes seeds from other species from germinating nearby. Creosote bush often reproduces vegetatively; when one plant dies, the crown spilts, producing several clonal plants. One clonal ring of cresosote bush in the Mojave Desert has been estimated to be 11,700 years old.
The flow of energy through any ecosystem starts with the fixation of sunlight by plants and other autotrophic organisms.
Lagomorphs are mammals of the family Lagomorpha.  They have four incisors in their upper jaw and are almost always herbivorous. Rabbits, hares, cottontails, and pika are all lagomorphs.

A mycorrhiza is a symbiotic (generally mutualistic) association between a fungus and the roots of a vascular plants. There are two main types of mycorrhiza: endomycorrhizae, where fungi directly enter the roots of the plant, and ectomycorrhizae, which forms a sheath around the roots. Over 90% of plant families use mychorrizal associations; many (grapes, roses, orchids) are completely dependent and can struggle to survive or germinate without the mycorrhizal association.
A small, lentic body of water that is either natural or man-made in origin. It may be permanent or ephemeral in nature.
A recreational or commercial endeavor with the purpose of capturing fish.
The amount of snow that an area receives in a year.
Species of the class Aves or clade Avialae. They are characterized by feathers, a beak with no teeth, the laying of eggs, and a lightweight skeleton.

The distribution of vegetation biomass horizontally and vertically. This can describe stand-level vegetation structure (canopy, subcanopy, shrub layer, and understory), or smaller-scale structure (e.g. shrubs, grasses, and leaf litter).
Water infiltration is the process by which water on the ground surface enters the soil.
Plant species: Sedum spathulifolium. A California native perennial herb in the Crassulaceae family.
The flow of water over the ground surface toward a stream channel or water body. Surface flow is typically derived from rain or snowmelt.

Topography is the description of the physical features of a specific place. It refers to natural and man made structures that make up the shape of a landscape including mountains, valleys, plains, lakes, rivers, and vegetation as well as roads, boundaries, transmission lines, and major buildings.

Compaction is a process in which stress is applied to soil causing densification as air is displaced from the pores between the soil grains. Normally, compaction is the result of heavy machinery compressing the soil, but it can also occur due to the passage of foot traffic from animals or humans.

Wildfire risk is the chance that a wildfire will start in or reach a particular area. Risk is dependent on variable factors such as human activities, weather patterns, availability of wildfire fuels, and the availability or lack of resources to suppress a fire.[
Anything that interferes or impedes a species ability to hear biologically relevant sounds.
An animal that feeds on dead or decaying organic matter.
Insects of the order Hemiptera (true bugs) and suborder Auchenorrhyncha, found in temperate to tropical climates. Cicadas are herbivores that feed primarily on tree sap.
The course, or set of courses, in which subsurface water in the saturated zone moves from areas of recharge to areas of discharge.
Surface/subsurface water exchange is the exchange of water that occurs within the hyporheic zone which lies beneath and alongside a streambed.
Habitat fragmentation involves alteration of habitat resulting in spatial separation of habitat units from a previous state of greater continuity.

Aquatic plants that are rooted in the bottom of a lakebed, streambed, marsh, or similar habitat; they have a large portion of their leaves, stems, flowers, or other structures protruding above the surface of the water. Emergent aquatic plants are found in both fresh or saltwater environments.
Areas designed to encourage wildlife to cross areas while minimizing risk to the species.
Plants indigenous to a given area in geologic time.
Plants indigenous to a given area in geologic time.

A clade of endothermic amniotes distinguished from reptiles and birds by the possession of hair, three middle ear bones, mammary glands, and a neocortex. The mammalian brain regulates body temperature and the circulatory system, including the four-chambered heart.
An animal or plant is colonizing habitat again
Occurs when dredging through the removal and relocating of sediments.
Fields where crops are cultivated
An animal in a wild state.
Mammals of the order Chiroptera whose forelimbs form webbed wings, making them the only mammals naturally capable of true and sustained flight.
The blueback herring (Alosa aestivalis) is an anadromous species of herring from the east coast of North America from Cape Breton, Nova Scotia, to the St. Johns River in Florida.

Bluefish (Pomatomus saltatrix) is the only extant species of the family Pomatomidae. It is a marine pelagic fish found around the world in temperate and subtropical waters, except for the northern Pacific Ocean. Bluefish are known as tailor in Australia, shad on the east coast of South Africa, and elf on the west coast. Other common names are blue, chopper, and anchoa.
The percent of a fixed area covered by the crown of an individual plant species or delimited by the vertical projection of its outermost perimeter.
Human altered sites that become suitable nesting areas (i.e., Salt pond dikes, artificial islands, dredge spoil mounds, airport medians).
Periods of darkness

Chilopods are a class of arthropods comprised of. Chilopods are made up of a chain of flattened body segments, each except the one behind the head and last two bearing a single pair of appendages. The appendages of the first body segment have been modified to form large, poisonous fangs that are used to capture prey.

Flatworms are a phylum of relatively simple bilaterian, unsegmented, soft-bodied invertebrates. They are acoelomates (having no body cavity), and have no specialized circulatory and respiratory organs, which restricts them to having flattened shapes that allow oxygen and nutrients to pass through their bodies by diffusion. The digestive cavity has only one opening for both the ingestion (intake of nutrients) and egestion (removal of undigested wastes).
General term for any number of grouse species (can be clarified in attributes) within the family Tetraonidae. Grouse are ground dwelling birds, many of which are managed as game.
the process of combining different varieties of organisms to create a hybrid.
Ionic regulation is the maintenance of the concentrations of the various ions in the body fluids relative to one another.
Trees with nests or nesting structures suitable for the species

features.displayName: spatial arrangement of vegetation that supports nest building
features.optionalDescription: This represents the structure required by the species to attach and build their nests
The tallest layer of vegetation (that includes living and dead) in vegetative community.
The layer of vegetation (living and dead) beneath the main canopy of a vegetation community.
Stable air temperature / sustained air temperature (no measurable or significant change)
This includes both legal and illegal cultivation
Animals eat more of foods based on their availability
Seacliff buckwheat (Eriogonum parvifolium) and coast buckwheat (Eriogonum latifolium)
Pools left in floodplain after river or stream floods

features.displayName: introduction of contaminants from runoff into freshwater environments
features.optionalDescription: Ground disturbing activities such as grading or excavation and stockpiling soils on land near freshwater environments can expose and release contaminants into the freshwater environment from rainfall and flooding runoff.
For northern spotted owl, this habitat functions for movement across the landscape to establish new territories, and gene flow. It must provide minimal foraging and roosting opportunities.
competition between animals for resources (food, habitat, etc)
The loss of water available to a species.
Grading activities changes the soil compaction by loosening the topsoil.
Mackerel is a common name applied to a number of different species of pelagic fish, mostly, but not exclusively, from the family Scombridae.
A mesopredator is a mid ranking predator in the middle of a trophic level, which typically preys on smaller animals.
Long-distance migrants typically move from breeding ranges to wintering grounds.
Symbiotic relationship between both fungus and vascular plants to benefit both.
Sound that is loud (above ambient levels)

Oceans become more acidic as carbon dioxide gas, the primary GHG, emitted into the atmosphere dissolves in the seawater, forming carbonic acid and changing the chemical composition of the ocean (IGBP et al. 2013, p. 14). The oceans have absorbed approximately 30 percent of all carbon dioxide released into the atmosphere by humans causing the pH level of the oceans to decrease.
The use of a vehicle off-road
Sea level rise is usually attributed to global climate change by thermal expansion of water in the oceans and by melting of ice sheets and glaciers on land.
Sea level rise is usually attributed to global climate change by thermal expansion of the water in the oceans and by melting of ice sheets and glaciers on land.
Having an indentation or inward curve.
Disease affecting hibernating bats associated with fungus, Geomyces destructans
competition between plant species for resources

Habitat that provides nesting opportunities for NSOs. Important stand elements may include high canopy closure (~70% or more), a multi-layered, multi-species canopy with larger overstory trees (average QMD of 26" DBH) and a presence of broken-topped trees or other nesting platforms (e.g., mistletoe clumps, broken tops, cavities). The appearance and structure of these forests will vary across the NSOs range particularly in dry forest provinces.
The process in living organisms involving the production of energy, typically with the intake of oxygen and the release of carbon dioxide from the oxidation of complex organic substances.
Remove exotic plants and revegetate existing blowout areas with native plants.

features.displayName: riparian vegetation with the appropriate spatial structure to support nest-building
features.optionalDescription: This represents the appropriate configuration for attaching and building nests

Foraging habitat structure in the understory for northern spotted owls

Density: Understory Stems: Low to moderate to allow for NSO maneuvering and foraging success Spatial arrangement: Mosaic of dense vegetation clusters interspersed with openings

Complex arrangement of shrubs, large down wood, leaning trees, saplings, other conifers 10" DBH or less, hardwoods within the understory of northern spotted owl nest stands, or Nesting/Roosting habitat. This resource need is required for fledglings to escape predation, and re-access the nest or lower- and mid-canopy roost sites. It also provides critical habitat resources for prey.

Canopy Cover: At least 60%
Density: High stem density
Height: Requires vertical and horizontal complexity and branching
Spatial arrangement: Mosaic of dense vegetation clusters interspersed with openings
An oil spill is the release of a liquid petroleum hydrocarbon into the environment, especially the marine ecosystem, due to human activity, and is a form of pollution.
Change in anthropogenic (human) activities (such as vehicular or pedestrian traffic) to an area.

DO NOT USE: WILL BE DELETED - Plankton are a diverse group of organisms that live in the water column of large bodies of water and that cannot swim against a current.These organisms include drifting animals, protists, archaea, algae, or bacteria that inhabit the pelagic zone of oceans, seas, or bodies of fresh water. They provide a crucial source of food to many large aquatic organisms, such as fish and whales.
Collapse of ground
rate of travel (i.e. boats, vehicles)

Density is the weight per unit volume of an object. Soil particle density excludes pore space and organic material. Soil bulk density includes air space and organic materials and is equal to the dry mass of the soil divided by the volume of the soil. A high bulk density is indicative of soil compaction. A lower bulk density by itself does not indicate suitability for plant growth due the influence of soil texture and structure. Soil bulk density is always less than the soil particle density.

A physical feature within a wetland that provides pockets of air for sheltering. These underground tunnels provide essential hibernacula for the bog turtle. Bog turtles also use these physical features for estivation.
Native species, including animals, plants, and other life forms. Can refer to native species assemblages as well as specific species.
Loss of rodents results in loss of rodent-constructed burrows. Rodent-constructed burrows are a resource need of hatchling tortoises (Nafus et al. 2017)
Amphipods are any member of the invertebrate order Amphipoda (class Crustacea) inhabiting all parts of the sea, lakes, rivers, sand beaches, caves, and moist (warm) habitats.
A narrow opening within a solid object.  Crevices can be found in rocks, trees, and woody debris

The life-supporting component of the air. Oxygen forms about 20 percent of the earth's atmosphere, and is the most abundant element in the earth's crust, mainly in the form of oxides, silicates, and carbonates.
A measure of the total pore space in the soil. ... The amount of porosity in a soil depends on the minerals that make up the soil and the amount of sorting that occurs within the soil structure.

Disruption of natural soil conditions. This can include large-scale disturbance of plants, or smaller-scale disturbance of pH and mineral conditions, affecting symbiotic relationships and the soil microbial community.

The amount of naturally occurring soil particles that is deposited into an environment over time. While this usually refers to deposition of sediment into aquatic systems, it may also refer to terrestrial habitats where it forms sedimentary rock.
Beetles are a group of insects that form the order Coleoptera. Their front pair of wings is hardened into wing-cases, elytra, distinguishing them from most other insects.
is a collection or association of plant species within a designated geographical unit, which forms a relatively uniform patch, distinguishable from neighboring patches of different vegetation types.
The ability of a plant or plants to generate new plants.

Coarse woody debris is comprised of fallen dead trees and the remains of large branches on the ground in forests and in rivers or wetlands. The minimum size required for woody debris to be defined as "coarse" varies by author, ranging from 2.520 cm (18 in) in diameter. Woody debris within streams and rivers are both a habitat feature for many species and factors that can significantly change the physical and biological characteristics of streams.
A contaminant is any substance, such as certain chemicals or waste products, that renders the air, soil, water, or other natural resource harmful or unsuitable for a specific purpose.
Driftwood is wood that has been washed onto a shore or beach of a sea, lake, or river by the action of winds, tides or waves.

A fruit is a part of a flowering plant that derives from specific tissues of the flower. Fruits are the means by which these plants disseminate seeds. Many of them that bear edible fruits and have propagated with the movements of humans and animals in a symbiotic relationship as a means for seed dispersal and nutrition.
Animals that primarily eat plant material, including deer, rabbits, and small rodents.
Human debris is man-made rubble, wreckage, ruins, discarded garbage/refuse/trash, and scattered remains of something destroyed and discarded.
Structures on the landscape built by humans. Bridges, houses, antennae towers, and roads are all examples of human structures.

The intertidal zone, also known as the foreshore and seashore and sometimes referred to as the littoral zone, is the area that is above water at low tide and under water at high tide (in other words, the area between tide marks).

Nectar is a sugar-rich liquid produced by plants in glands called nectaries, either within the flowers with which it attracts pollinating animals, or by extrafloral nectaries, which provide a nutrient source to animal mutualists, which in turn provide antiherbivore protection.

features.optionalDescription: This feature includes sea, ocean, bays, etc., that are considered open- or deep- water marine areas.

Phytoplankton are photosynthesizing microscopic organisms that inhabit the upper sunlit layer of almost all oceans and bodies of fresh water. Phytoplankton is essential as the base of all aquatic food webs.
Pollen is a fine to coarse powder containing the microgametophytes of seed plants, which produce the male gametes (sperm cells).
Composed of boulders, cobble, or gravel
The degree to which chemicals, toxins or poisons in water runoff can harm living organisms.
Sand or very small gravel substrate on channel bottom is preferred foraging habitat.
The settling out of suspended particles onto the stream bed.
a reserve of viable seeds present in the soil and on its surface
comparative darkness and coolness caused by shelter from direct sunlight
This category encompasses sheltered marine and estuarine areas such as: secluded canals, creeks, embayments, and lagoons.
Slabrocks are large flat rocks with a cavity  under it.
The flow of water from an aquifer to the earth's surface.
Drought resistant plants in which the leaves, stem or roots have become more than usually fleshy by the development of water-storing tissue.

Tidal inlet A narrow channel that connects the open sea with a lagoon. Tidal inlets often occur in barrier-island systems and are typified by small-scale deltas at each end of the inlets, resulting from the high-velocity, tidal-reversal currents that flow through the channels.

The upper, outermost layer of soil which has the highest concentration of organic matter and microorganisms. Plants generally concentrate their roots in and obtain most of their vital nutrients from this layer.

Vernal pools are seasonally inundated, freshwater pools made possible by a hardpan, clay soil layer that allows water retention.  These ephemeral wetlands are often used by obligate species requiring both the wet and dry phases of the annual cycle.
Tolerances to elevated temperature, reduced dissolved oxygen concentrations, elevated salinity, and turbidity.
Material that is deposited in an aquatic system but originatsd from terrestrial habitat.

This category includes vascular plants that are specially adapted to growing in aquatic environments; they grow only in water or in permanently saturated soil.  Aquatic vegetation includes those plants that float on the surface, those that are entirely submerged, and emergent rooted vegetation. This category does not include algae or seaweed

features.displayName: barriers to the movement of prey
features.optionalDescription: Structures or environmental conditions that inhibit or reduce the ability of prey to move on the landscape.

Bioaccumulation the accumulation of substances, such as pesticides, or other organic chemicals in an organism. Bioaccumulation occurs when an organism absorbs a toxic substance at a rate greater than that at which the substance is lost

Calcium carbonate is a chemical compound with the formula CaCO3. It is formed by three main elements: carbon, oxygen, and calcium. Calcium carbonate is a common substance found in rocks all over the world, and is the main component in the shells of marine organisms, snails, coal balls, pearls, and eggshells.
The measure of a cliff's resistance to pressure and erosion. Cliff stability can be influenced my multiple factors, including vegetative root systems and exposure to water and wind.
Land masses surrounded by water that are located relatively near to shore, but may occur in areas designated as either nearshore or offshore.
Interstitial water essential for soil-dependent life
Inundation occurs when terrestrial habitat becomes covered in water.

The zone of unconsolidated material in a coastal area that extends from the mean low water line to the place where there is a marked change in material or physiographic form, or to the line of permanent vegetation (the effective limit of storm waves and storm surge), i.e. to the coastline. The beach or shore can be divided into the foreshore and the backshore.

A marine region relatively close to shore that may include the intertidal zone (area between low tide and high tide marks) and/or portions of the subtidal zone (area below the low tide mark that remains submerged) where tides may influence water depth and flow over sandbars, shoals, mudflats and other features of the ocean floor.
The process of corroding metal, stone, or other materials.

Detritus is non-living particulate organic material. It typically includes the bodies or fragments of dead organisms as well as fecal material. Detritus is typically colonized by communities of microorganisms which act to decompose the material.
Limestone containing high levels of magnesium and calcium
A fine, dry powder consisting of tiny particles of earth or waste matter lying on the ground, on surfaces, or carried in the air:

An ecosystem's response to the addition of artificial or natural nutrients, mainly phosphates, through detergents, fertilizers, or sewage, to an aquatic system. One example is the "bloom" or great increase of phytoplankton in a water body as a response to increased levels of nutrients.
The state of being exposed to contact with something.
An overflow of water above the normal boundaries of a body of water that submerges dry land.
A floodplain is the land adjacent to a river, stream, lake, or similar that is regularly covered by water during times of high flow.
The amount of combustible material within a given space or habitat; it is often defined in heat units or in terms of the amount of wood.

Ground water recharge is defined as the natural process of infiltration and percolation of rainwater from land areas or streams through permeable soils into water-holding rocks or unconsolidated materials (such as sands and gravels) that provide underground storage in saturated zones known as ground water; where the ground water can yield good water supplies to wells it is known as an aquifer.
The place where a hibernating animal shelters, usually for the winter.
a tank or artificial pond used for watering livestock
Organic debris is the remnants of dead plants and animals that lived in the ecosystem. Examples of this are fallen trees, brush piles, leaf litter, and bones.
Dogs and cats!

An animal, as the horse or cat, that has been tamed and kept by humans as a work animal, food source, or pet, especially a member of those species that have, through selective breeding, become notably different from their wild ancestors.
Separation from like species.
Snow of sufficient depth and pliable consistency for construction of snow roosts needed for nighttime shelter.

A process by which water becomes dirty as a result of fine mineral particles (particle size dominated by silt or clay) in the water. These particles eventually settle and become part of the substrate.

Smoke is a collection of airborne solid and liquid particulates and gases emitted when a material undergoes combustion or pyrolysis, together with the quantity of air that is entrained or otherwise mixed into the mass. It is commonly an unwanted by-product of fires.
The compacting and hardening of snow.  This can inhibit use by some species and make travel easier for other species.
Most plants obtain key nutrients from soil, such as nitrogen, phosphorous, potassium, and magnesium.

Water moving through fractures in the limestone, dissolved the limestone and eroded the fractures until a larger tunnel, or pipe, forms. Over time, the soil above the eroded limestone can no longer be supported. The pipe then collapses, and the sinkhole opens up at the surface and soil fell into the void below.
The ability of a streambank to resist erosional forces and retain structure.
Temperature of ground elements that are not soil (e.g. rock)
The form and function of streams and the interaction between streams and the landscape around them.
Many species require sunlight to fulfill their life history needs. Most plants contain chloroplasts, which require sunlight to obtain energy via photosynthesis.
The rate at which trees increase in volume and/or height.

The components of natural water, whether in the atmosphere, on the ground surface, or under the ground, which always contain dissolved minerals and gases as a result of its interaction with the atmosphere, minerals in rocks, organic matter, and living organisms.
The degree in which vegetation or structure shade a stream. Stream shading plays an important role in water temperatures and the abundance of food inputs.

An assemblage of plant species and the ground cover they provide. It is a general term, without specific reference to particular taxa, life forms, structure, spatial extent, or any other specific botanical or geographic characteristics.
Ground disturbing activities such as grading or excavation and stockpiling of soils near freshwater environments that can expose and release contaminants into rainfall or flood runoff
Removal of sandy soils decreases foraging and sheltering habitat which the Houston toad depends upon.
Structure that prevents adequate flow of water essential for reproduction.
